caption: If a 25 dollar old fashioned is in your pocket, then you’ll love this place. Where else can you argue with a mixologist on which bitters is the best? Oh wait, basically anywhere in Logan. Hope Billy Sunday survives lockdown and we can spend the money we saved from not going out on these glorious cocktails. Bring your platinum or black Amex.
Fun little bar with tasty cocktails

Billy Sunday is a cocktail enthusiast's wet-bar dream in the most unassuming of digs.  Their staff has all of the talent, creativity, and precision that you find at the Aviary, Pouring Ribbons, or Silver Lyan, but packaged into a cozy bar without any pretentiousness getting in the way of a finely crafted drink.  Behind their bar is a collection of modern classics and vintage gems and their bar staff are friendly powerhouses of knowledge and skill.  The bar is spotless clean and strictly enforces allcovid precautions - so enjoy their patio while the weather holds.  After winter sets in, their take-home service and tasting classes are on point - especially if you're new to craft spirits or you find asking questions in a busy bar intimidating, the classes and to-go service give you a more private access to their staff from the confort of your own home, and the team are fantastic about sharing what they know at whatever level you're at.  Just come with an open mind and a willingness to enjoy something new.  I found Billy Sunday because they are recognized for the largest collection of vintage Amaro in the US - a fact lauded in every book published on the subject.  I stayed because they're awesome people that welcome you like an old friend.  Whether you love booze like I do, or just want to sound more impressive at parties (once we can safely have them again) then you should head up to their bar and drink your way through their menu - just keep your hands off the 1960's Cynar until I can get a few more pours.

Nice bar, nice bartender, NOT WORTH THE COCKTAIL CLASS. The class is offered on eventbrite (cocktail 101 and cocktail 102). It is advertised as a class where you make your own cocktails and have 3 cocktails. You do not make your own cocktails. The bartender makes the cocktails while talking through them. Also, you don’t get your own drinks. You share a cocktail with 5 other strangers and get 1 sip. So basically you pay $55 plus tip for 3 sips of a cocktail while watching somebody make you drinks and talk through them. 100% not worth it. Save your money and do an actual cocktail class if that is what you are seeking.

I was very hesitant to try the Papa Don't Peach since it had egg white in it, but I tried and it wasn't bad! I don't remember anything about Kent or Baby Darlin', but I know I tried them.  As for food, our group tried the gooey butter cake, which was good as a standalone cake with the berry compote, but not a gooey butter cake by any means. It was too dry. Very disappointed in Billy Sunday's choice of naming a drink called "Leaving Saigon" outside.  For the record, I'm Vietnamese American, and my family was forced to leave Vietnam after the Vietcong took over the South.  The trauma of my family's experience, along with hundreds of thousands that left their homeland is still present in those minds, and for your establishment, let alone a non-Vietnamese one that caters mostly to a hipster crowd is offensive and disregards the history and trauma of US intervention in my family homeland.  It is a punch in the face to the Vietnamese community here, former Vietnam War vets who left Saigon with forever PTSD when you name this after a silly drink of yours.  Better check your history, and be a little smart next time. Shame on you for exploiting the war and its generation of survivors

One thing is readily apparent after spending a short while in Billy Sunday—every detail has been crafted by purpose. From the unique and antique furnishings that accent the bar and create a truly splendid atmosphere, to the library of rare international liquors, Billy Sunday is a shrine to the art of the cocktail.  While the menu is fun, unique, and progressive enough to allow a patron to find a drink for nearly whatever their taste-du-jour may be, I recommend asking the bartender to help you find a new favorite off-menu. With their extensive experience (and clearly passionate study), they are sure to hit the mark. And your visit, like ours, might turn into a fun learning experience...  My favorite is the House twist on a negroni.

Whether casual or critical, this dimly lit and buzzing location offers the best in exotic and creative elixirs, designed by an award-winning team of mixologists. Also if you can grab a seat outside, it's worth it (I incidentally found parking in Logan square right next to this bar which is how I discovered this place). Regardless, the inside is also cool and definitely has a hipster vibe to it. The food on the other hand was pretty good, but not the best in town, I had pickles and bread here and they were overpriced, and thats the other downside and why they don't get a 5 star rating, their prices are kind of expensive for the neighborhood, I mean all of their cocktails are $13+

Alex knocks it out of the park time and time again with a menu full of variety. Seasonality is a big focus here, and the drink styles change to suit your wardrobe. Don't forget about the food - everything I had was excellent.

My husband and I showed up at 7 pm on a Friday and snagged two seats at the bar. I immediately fell in love with the dark, gray space. The drink menu is intimidating, given I could only identify 1-2 ingredients in each cocktail. Luckily, the bartender was really knowledgeable and not at all pretentious. I went with a tequila tonic that was really refreshing!  I'm not a huge fan of whisky, but one sip of my husband's cocktail was enough to change my mind. I can't wait to go back and try more of the menu!

Solid craft cocktails; started with the tonic flight which featured a rye, a rum, a gin and a tequila based cocktail.  Was great to sample and swap with friends (if you were not particularly to one).  Friends like the Algren's Cocktail (smooth and sweet).  My favorite was the Grapes, Rice and Wrath.  I wished they had a more extensive dinner menu, but we chowed down on the Pimento Cheese and the Crab Dib.  Pretty tasty.

Trendiest new cocktail bar concept in Logan Square. Amazing steak tartare. House made tonics also sets this place apart from the other cocktail concepts in town. Less pretentious than Violet Hour, friendly staff, and usually much shorter wait. Bar is also owned by the same group that owns Yusho.

Dangerously strong cocktails - try the flight of tonics.  They have totlly wierd-sounding ingredients but they all taste delicious,  You won't realise how drunk you are until you get up and try and walk out......

Went here with the girls on a Tuesday. Their tonics were delicious and we had a variety of drinks that made for some fun. The time you have at a place depends on the company, so needless to say we had a great time! BIlly Sunday provided a great backdrop for that.
Nice outdoor patio. Strong drinks.

You come for the cocktails at Billy Sunday but you can stay for the food. They have a wonderful drink menu including ones made with homemade tonic and an imposing number of rare bottles behind the bar. For a cocktail bar the food is up snuff. I would skip the pig ears (salty) and opt for the pot pie or something in a jar (all were quite tasty).
My friend is the head bartender there, so that's great. I think the drinks are over-priced, but it's a fun environment.

Good drinks and the desserts we tried were both delicious. As other have mentioned it is very dark inside but I guess that adds to the ambience they are going for. I liked the Cocktail quite a bit and look forward to coming back to try some other drinks soon.

I came here on a Saturday night and it was fairly easy to get a table.  I was really excited to visit this place based on reviews.  However, the drinks are fairly over-priced considering that it is located in Logan Square.

Come here if you want to feel like you're eating in a Portlandia skit.  They won't server tempelton becuase "it doesn't taste like it used to" but the cocktails they make are amazing and the atmosphere is fun.  Try the steak tartar with pickel chips.

Went here for quick drinks and the pudding, and both were massive tasty!  I had the Old Fashioned - its a bit sweeter than I expected but still good; had an unusual (to me) ice cube, or rather an ice sphere for keeping the cocktail cool; a nice touch. Also had the banana pudding - yummy with the cookie too, a must try for a quick dessert or snack.  Staff was friendly and fairly quick - will go here again, especially when playing Ingress or attending the next Cut & Paste.
Cool vibe, limited well executed food.

Very dark space but efficient service. Employees take order on a tablet and never messed up an order. The drinks were well made and amazing. The food was small but filling. We had potpies that were cheesy and savory. Service was impeccable!

Billy Sunday is new-ish to the Logan Square scene.  For the area, I feel that it's a little pricey.  The environment is dimly lit and done up with random pieces of flatware and dishware that you might find at a thrift shop.  The food is decent but I'd really only come back for the drinks due to the price.
